00:01:19.830 --> 00:01:22.600
So we already talked
about a filter.

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:25.080
I motivated a filter by
thinking about Fourier series

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:26.880
because it's easy.

00:01:26.880 --> 00:01:29.910
If you think about
the system that's

00:01:29.910 --> 00:01:32.610
comprised of a resistor
and a capacitor,

00:01:32.610 --> 00:01:35.200
and you have as an input
vi and an output vo,

00:01:35.200 --> 00:01:38.490
then you can think about
that system being a filter.

00:01:38.490 --> 00:01:41.700
The filter can be characterized
by a frequency response.

00:01:41.700 --> 00:01:44.220
You're all experts at that.

00:01:44.220 --> 00:01:48.840
And then if you can break the
signal into Fourier components,

00:01:48.840 --> 00:01:51.816
which was easy when we
had a Fourier series,

00:01:51.816 --> 00:01:53.940
if you can break the signal
into Fourier components

00:01:53.940 --> 00:02:00.180
then it's easy to calculate the
output as the sum of weighted

00:02:00.180 --> 00:02:02.580
and possibly time
shifted versions

00:02:02.580 --> 00:02:04.230
of the components of the input.

00:02:04.230 --> 00:02:07.890
So we can decompose the
signal, the square wave,

00:02:07.890 --> 00:02:11.610
into a bunch of
Fourier components.

00:02:11.610 --> 00:02:14.550
And then think about how
they pass through the filter.

00:02:14.550 --> 00:02:17.100
Where if they all pass
through the low frequency

00:02:17.100 --> 00:02:21.540
part of the filter, so that the
gain is one and the phase is 0,

00:02:21.540 --> 00:02:23.470
the output looks
just like the input.

00:02:23.470 --> 00:02:26.550
And if they all pass through
the part of the filter that's

00:02:26.550 --> 00:02:28.535
sloping down with
a slope of minus 1,

00:02:28.535 --> 00:02:31.230
with the phase
lagging by pi over 2,

00:02:31.230 --> 00:02:33.130
you turn a square wave
into a triangle wave.

00:02:33.130 --> 00:02:35.340
That was the simplest
example of a filter.

00:02:35.340 --> 00:02:40.440
We saw it again when we thought
about speech production.

00:02:40.440 --> 00:02:44.220
Because there the idea was that
the different kinds of sounds

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:47.820
that we make are partially
generated by the larynx,

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:51.270
and partially generated
by the throat.

00:02:51.270 --> 00:02:53.950
And it's all the
musculature in your face

00:02:53.950 --> 00:02:59.610
that enables you to make the
precise different sounds.

00:02:59.610 --> 00:03:01.620
And that was what we
called the source filter

00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:03.120
model of speech production.

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:06.270
The sources down here,
the filter is here.

00:03:06.270 --> 00:03:10.410
And we again, we can think about
it by thinking about filtering.

00:03:10.410 --> 00:03:12.270
Filtering comes up
all over the place,

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:14.700
and it's one of the most
important applications

00:03:14.700 --> 00:03:17.340
of Fourier techniques generally.

00:03:17.340 --> 00:03:19.860
And it's for all the
reasons you already know.

00:03:19.860 --> 00:03:21.870
If you can think of a
way of breaking down

00:03:21.870 --> 00:03:24.000
a signal into
Fourier components,

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.440
then you can thing about
an LTI system as a filter.

00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:33.930
And in filtering applications,
in signal processing filtering

00:03:33.930 --> 00:03:35.550
applications, we
usually try to think

00:03:35.550 --> 00:03:37.810
about high frequencies,
low frequencies,

00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:39.510
designing systems
that pass the lows,

00:03:39.510 --> 00:03:41.260
pass the highs,
that sort of thing.

00:03:41.260 --> 00:03:43.090
But the key is
breaking down an input,

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:46.200
which might be
complicated in the pieces.

00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:49.350
That's where the Fourier
transform is so good.

00:03:49.350 --> 00:03:50.910
And so, I want to
illustrate that

00:03:50.910 --> 00:03:53.940
by thinking about a hard
problem in signal processing,

00:03:53.940 --> 00:03:57.180
and that is an
electrocardiogram.

00:03:57.180 --> 00:03:59.220
So first off, it's
completely amazing

00:03:59.220 --> 00:04:02.920
that you can measure an
electrocardiogram at all.

00:04:02.920 --> 00:04:05.280
The voltages
produced by cells are

00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:07.930
on the order of 100 millivolts.

00:04:07.930 --> 00:04:11.040
That's true for all cells for
extremely fundamental reasons,

00:04:11.040 --> 00:04:14.310
which if you're interested in,
6021 has a lot of information

00:04:14.310 --> 00:04:15.390
about why.

00:04:15.390 --> 00:04:17.880
There are fundamental
physical limits

00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:21.750
on what kinds of a
voltage a cell can make.

00:04:21.750 --> 00:04:28.170
So the voltages are small, but
they're much worse than that,

00:04:28.170 --> 00:04:30.360
they're constrained to
the inside of a cell.

00:04:30.360 --> 00:04:33.207
You can't generally get access
to the inside of a cell.

00:04:33.207 --> 00:04:35.290
In fact, there's a big
technological breakthrough,

00:04:35.290 --> 00:04:37.140
and people figured
out how to draw--

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:39.030
cells are little.

00:04:39.030 --> 00:04:41.820
It's kind of hard to
imagine how little they are.

00:04:41.820 --> 00:04:48.870
About two to three million
cells would fit in the length,

00:04:48.870 --> 00:04:52.032
in a one inch length
of a human hair.

00:04:52.032 --> 00:04:53.490
And that's a skinny
hair like mine.

00:04:53.490 --> 00:04:57.240
So blonde skinny hair.

00:04:57.240 --> 00:05:00.480
The rest is not necessarily
skinny, but they're skinny.

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:02.400
So you can get about
a million cells,

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:07.200
maybe two million cells in
one length, one inch of--

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:08.757
length of a human hair.

00:05:08.757 --> 00:05:10.590
To give you some idea
of how small they are.

00:05:10.590 --> 00:05:12.110
These tiny, tiny,
tiny little things.

00:05:12.110 --> 00:05:13.020
So it was a big deal
when people were

00:05:13.020 --> 00:05:14.552
able to measure inside a cell.

00:05:14.552 --> 00:05:16.260
And when you put
electrodes on your chest

00:05:16.260 --> 00:05:19.920
to measure an electrocardiogram,
you're not inside a cell.

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:22.510
Cells are surrounded
by an insulator.

00:05:22.510 --> 00:05:26.760
So not much of that electrical
current is available to you.

00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:31.710
Furthermore, the cells in the
heart are surrounded by saline.

00:05:31.710 --> 00:05:34.600
What's important about saline?

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:37.400
What is saline?

00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:38.621
Salt water.

00:05:38.621 --> 00:05:39.870
What's important about saline?

00:05:42.804 --> 00:05:44.220
What would be
different if we were

00:05:44.220 --> 00:05:47.160
filled with distilled water?

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:50.810
Besides the fact
that we would die.

00:05:50.810 --> 00:05:52.590
Yeah.

00:05:52.590 --> 00:05:54.310
Conducts electricity.

00:05:54.310 --> 00:05:57.810
So the fluid that
bathes the cells

00:05:57.810 --> 00:05:59.950
has a very high
ionic concentration.

00:05:59.950 --> 00:06:02.784
And that means that it
conducts electricity,

00:06:02.784 --> 00:06:04.200
which means most
of the potentials

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:06.866
are shorted out before they ever
get to the surface of the skin.

00:06:06.866 --> 00:06:09.900
Then there's another 20
layers of insulation,

00:06:09.900 --> 00:06:12.540
called your skin.

00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:15.760
So it's astonishing that you
can even measure these things.

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:17.310
And when you do,
it's not surprising

00:06:17.310 --> 00:06:20.850
that there's a lot of
signal in the waveform,

00:06:20.850 --> 00:06:22.750
other than the signal
that you intend.

00:06:22.750 --> 00:06:27.300
There's about 10 to the
13th neurons in your body,

00:06:27.300 --> 00:06:29.460
and they're all chattering away.

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:30.850
So you see those.

00:06:30.850 --> 00:06:34.950
So that the idea of filtering
out the part of the signal

00:06:34.950 --> 00:06:37.862
that results from the EKG
is completely non-trivial.

00:06:37.862 --> 00:06:40.320
And it's very useful to think
about it in a Fourier domain.

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:42.870
And absolutely everybody
does it that way.

00:06:42.870 --> 00:06:47.220
If you were to take the Fourier
transform of this waveform,

00:06:47.220 --> 00:06:48.720
you would get a
wave form that looks

00:06:48.720 --> 00:06:51.420
like this, which looks
perhaps more complicated.

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:53.820
except that you can make
some sense out of it.

00:06:53.820 --> 00:06:56.130
Hearts beat about 60
or 70 times a minute,

00:06:56.130 --> 00:06:59.340
depending on how athletic
and how old you are,

00:06:59.340 --> 00:07:03.480
which means that it's
the components around 1

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:07.020
or bigger that are
coming from the heart.

00:07:07.020 --> 00:07:09.007
Things significantly
lower than hertz

00:07:09.007 --> 00:07:10.590
probably aren't
coming from the heart.

00:07:10.590 --> 00:07:13.170
Things that are up in the
10 kilohertz region probably

00:07:13.170 --> 00:07:16.390
are not from the heart.

00:07:16.390 --> 00:07:21.040
This enormous
spike, what's that?

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:22.510
That's the lights.

00:07:22.510 --> 00:07:23.680
That's the power.

00:07:23.680 --> 00:07:28.450
That's the-- we distribute
electrical power by modulating

00:07:28.450 --> 00:07:30.670
it at 60 hertz because
that distributes better,

00:07:30.670 --> 00:07:32.380
but then it radiates.

00:07:32.380 --> 00:07:37.300
And so some of that can be
coupled into everything,

00:07:37.300 --> 00:07:39.430
including me.

00:07:39.430 --> 00:07:42.520
So the big line is
the 60 hertz that's

00:07:42.520 --> 00:07:46.720
being coupled from the
power distribution network

00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:50.260
into the person
whose EKG this is.

00:07:50.260 --> 00:07:52.450
So what we'd like to
do then is generate

00:07:52.450 --> 00:07:56.620
a filter that takes out
the stuff that isn't EKG.

00:07:56.620 --> 00:07:58.840
So we'd like to eliminate
this low frequency stuff,

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:02.380
and we'd like to eliminate this
high frequency stuff, right?

00:08:02.380 --> 00:08:05.710
So what we do is
we design a filter.

00:08:05.710 --> 00:08:08.870
Filter design Bode of course.

00:08:08.870 --> 00:08:09.370
Right?

00:08:09.370 --> 00:08:10.060
Smile?

00:08:10.060 --> 00:08:11.640
Everybody smile, you know?

00:08:11.640 --> 00:08:16.270
There's nothing on a quiz
for weeks to come, right?

00:08:16.270 --> 00:08:17.440
So Bode.

00:08:17.440 --> 00:08:21.580
So we would think about
passing the high frequencies.

00:08:25.730 --> 00:08:27.080
I didn't say that right.

00:08:27.080 --> 00:08:29.330
So we would like to
cut off the very lows,

00:08:29.330 --> 00:08:32.210
we'd like to cut
off the very highs.

00:08:32.210 --> 00:08:36.830
And we'd like to get rid of
that one glitch at 60 hertz.

00:08:36.830 --> 00:08:40.280
So the 60 hertz thing, that's
what this is intended to do.

00:08:40.280 --> 00:08:42.950
It's intended to be a
very narrow filter that

00:08:42.950 --> 00:08:46.130
just wipes out the 60.

00:08:46.130 --> 00:08:49.220
So this is a kind of filter
that I'd like to design.

00:08:49.220 --> 00:08:51.410
And here is the design.

00:08:51.410 --> 00:08:54.110
Handful of poles and 0s.

00:08:54.110 --> 00:08:59.450
Your task, talk to your neighbor
and figure out which poles

00:08:59.450 --> 00:09:01.550
and which 0s go with the
high pass, the low pass,

00:09:01.550 --> 00:09:02.133
and the notch.

00:09:07.760 --> 00:09:09.745
Look at your neighbor,
say hi, smile.

00:10:53.340 --> 00:10:57.090
OK, so which of the poles and
0s contribute to the high pass?

00:11:00.295 --> 00:11:01.170
Rught, you can point.

00:11:01.170 --> 00:11:04.300
Like, there's up, and there's
left, and there's center.

00:11:04.300 --> 00:11:05.859
So which ones are high pass?

00:11:11.130 --> 00:11:12.000
The ones near 0.

00:11:14.816 --> 00:11:16.986
The 0 or the poles?

00:11:16.986 --> 00:11:18.360
Or one of each,
or both, or what?

00:11:24.270 --> 00:11:29.464
So what would the Bode plot
look like if you only had the 0?

00:11:29.464 --> 00:11:30.340
Yeah.

00:11:30.340 --> 00:11:36.740
So the 0 alone would cancel
out frequency components at 0.

00:11:36.740 --> 00:11:41.092
Which our Bode plot is
a way over there, right?

00:11:41.092 --> 00:11:42.050
What about these poles?

00:11:42.050 --> 00:11:42.924
What's the poles for?

00:11:46.470 --> 00:11:48.450
They flatten that it out.

00:11:48.450 --> 00:11:50.390
So if you think
about reading off

00:11:50.390 --> 00:11:53.330
the effect of the poles
and 0s starting at 0

00:11:53.330 --> 00:11:57.047
and going to bigger
and bigger radiuses,

00:11:57.047 --> 00:11:58.630
then the first thing
you have to worry

00:11:58.630 --> 00:12:01.300
about going left to
right on the Bode plot,

00:12:01.300 --> 00:12:04.090
is the 0s doing this.

00:12:04.090 --> 00:12:06.040
And then these poles
flatten out the 0s.

00:12:10.030 --> 00:12:13.310
So what's this doing?

00:12:13.310 --> 00:12:16.570
That's the thing
that's attenuating

00:12:16.570 --> 00:12:19.510
the high frequencies,
which leaves us with this.

00:12:19.510 --> 00:12:21.286
What's that?

00:12:21.286 --> 00:12:22.660
And how do you
know it's a notch?

00:12:25.366 --> 00:12:27.110
There's a 0.

00:12:27.110 --> 00:12:29.960
So the 0 on the
j-omega axis means

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:33.370
there's a frequency that
it completely wipes out.

00:12:33.370 --> 00:12:35.710
Why do I need to have
this stupid pole here?

00:12:35.710 --> 00:12:37.860
Can't I just put the 0 there?

00:12:37.860 --> 00:12:39.640
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:39.640 --> 00:12:41.330
DENNIS FREEMAN:
Bring it back up.

00:12:41.330 --> 00:12:46.990
So the idea is that if you
put the pole close to the 0,

00:12:46.990 --> 00:12:49.820
if you get to a frequency that's
pretty far away from those,

00:12:49.820 --> 00:12:51.770
their effects
cancel, and there's

00:12:51.770 --> 00:12:54.200
no effect of either of them.

00:12:54.200 --> 00:12:57.080
So their effect is
constrained to frequencies

00:12:57.080 --> 00:13:03.620
that are very close measured
in terms of this distance.

00:13:03.620 --> 00:13:06.680
So you have to be at a frequency
that's very close in order

00:13:06.680 --> 00:13:09.830
to have an effect.

00:13:09.830 --> 00:13:13.160
And when you do that, when
you design such a filter,

00:13:13.160 --> 00:13:14.570
you clean up the
wave form a lot,

00:13:14.570 --> 00:13:19.580
and no one in their right mind
would generate an EKG machine

00:13:19.580 --> 00:13:20.720
that didn't do this.

00:13:20.720 --> 00:13:23.660
I mean, that's just built
into the preamplifier that's

00:13:23.660 --> 00:13:25.070
attached to the electrodes.

00:13:25.070 --> 00:13:28.970
So the point is that filtering
is very important application

00:13:28.970 --> 00:13:30.590
of Fourier transforms.

00:13:30.590 --> 00:13:33.980
We can take an arbitrary signal
and often get a lot of insight

00:13:33.980 --> 00:13:38.060
into what we would like to
preserve and remove by thinking

00:13:38.060 --> 00:13:39.770
about the Fourier
transform, insights

00:13:39.770 --> 00:13:42.061
that you wouldn't get by
looking at the time wave form.

00:13:44.780 --> 00:13:47.650
Next thing I want to think
about is a little bit different.

00:13:47.650 --> 00:13:50.080
I want to think about physics.

00:13:50.080 --> 00:13:52.960
This isn't, of course, in
physics, nor am I a physicist,

00:13:52.960 --> 00:13:56.410
but I do do optics.

00:13:56.410 --> 00:13:59.267
And the thing I want to
think about is diffraction.

00:13:59.267 --> 00:14:00.850
You can't understand
optics unless you

00:14:00.850 --> 00:14:03.370
think about diffraction,
and honestly the easiest way

00:14:03.370 --> 00:14:11.100
to think about diffraction
is Fourier transform.

00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:13.510
So a very simple
example of diffraction.

00:14:13.510 --> 00:14:15.870
So here is a
diffraction grating.

00:14:15.870 --> 00:14:19.230
So if I pass a coherent beam
through there, which I just

00:14:19.230 --> 00:14:22.560
happen to have, if I
pass a coherent beam

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:24.650
through a diffraction
grating, what do you see?

00:14:29.840 --> 00:14:33.490
The diffraction
grating split one beam.

00:14:33.490 --> 00:14:36.350
All term I've been
pointing with one.

00:14:36.350 --> 00:14:41.130
Well, if I put this in front
of it, now I get three.

00:14:41.130 --> 00:14:45.700
So somehow there's
something about this that's

00:14:45.700 --> 00:14:47.365
breaking one beam into three.

00:14:49.980 --> 00:14:52.960
Can you think why?

00:14:52.960 --> 00:14:58.750
Can you remember 802 where
they probably mentioned this?

00:15:02.440 --> 00:15:03.515
What is this?

00:15:07.170 --> 00:15:08.318
What's in here?

00:15:08.318 --> 00:15:10.070
AUDIENCE: Slits.

00:15:10.070 --> 00:15:11.170
DENNIS FREEMAN: Slits.

00:15:11.170 --> 00:15:11.770
Close.

00:15:11.770 --> 00:15:13.420
Yeah.

00:15:13.420 --> 00:15:15.430
So the simplest
experiment where you

00:15:15.430 --> 00:15:18.385
could illustrate this kind of
a diffraction phenomenon is--

00:15:21.570 --> 00:15:22.425
goes by the name--

00:15:26.460 --> 00:15:27.020
yes.

00:15:27.020 --> 00:15:27.650
Shout the name.

00:15:31.140 --> 00:15:33.775
Young.

00:15:33.775 --> 00:15:35.619
AUDIENCE: Double
slit experiment.

00:15:35.619 --> 00:15:37.940
DENNIS FREEMAN: Double
slit experiment.

00:15:37.940 --> 00:15:41.090
So if you pass light
through two slits,

00:15:41.090 --> 00:15:42.470
something phenomenal happens.

00:15:42.470 --> 00:15:46.370
And it's very closely
related to this.

00:15:46.370 --> 00:15:47.120
What's in this?

00:15:49.862 --> 00:15:51.690
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:51.690 --> 00:15:54.470
DENNIS FREEMAN:
Something like a slit.

00:15:54.470 --> 00:15:57.790
It's actually something
like a whole bunch of slits.

00:15:57.790 --> 00:15:58.310
So, yeah?

00:15:58.310 --> 00:15:59.196
AUDIENCE: Polarizer.

00:15:59.196 --> 00:16:00.370
DENNIS FREEMAN: Polarizer.

00:16:00.370 --> 00:16:01.560
Close.

00:16:01.560 --> 00:16:06.286
It's one of those neat words
from physics, but not quite.

00:16:06.286 --> 00:16:07.660
Polarized has to
do with the fact

00:16:07.660 --> 00:16:10.540
that the light has an
e field and an m field,

00:16:10.540 --> 00:16:12.280
and they are perpendicular
to each other,

00:16:12.280 --> 00:16:16.580
and sources like this one
actually keep them separate.

00:16:16.580 --> 00:16:19.120
So this actually does
generate polarized light,

00:16:19.120 --> 00:16:23.230
but you can't really tell
because if I spin the laser

00:16:23.230 --> 00:16:24.940
pointer, you can't
really see anything.

00:16:24.940 --> 00:16:26.065
But if I spin the grating--

00:16:30.760 --> 00:16:31.840
I just said something.

00:16:31.840 --> 00:16:33.311
So what did I just call this?

00:16:33.311 --> 00:16:34.060
AUDIENCE: Grating.

00:16:34.060 --> 00:16:35.380
DENNIS FREEMAN: Grating.

00:16:35.380 --> 00:16:37.136
So what is it?

00:16:37.136 --> 00:16:38.260
It's a diffraction grating.

00:16:38.260 --> 00:16:43.880
It's got a bunch of little
horizontal structure.

00:16:43.880 --> 00:16:47.770
So the idea is here.

00:16:47.770 --> 00:16:51.460
The grating, you can think
about it as an array,

00:16:51.460 --> 00:16:53.410
big array, big
compared to the size

00:16:53.410 --> 00:16:55.360
of the point that
I was eliminating,

00:16:55.360 --> 00:17:00.040
big array of scatterers.

00:17:00.040 --> 00:17:03.010
So you think about
having a material that

00:17:03.010 --> 00:17:05.200
transmits light
and a material that

00:17:05.200 --> 00:17:08.109
scatters light and a material
that scatters light is arranged

00:17:08.109 --> 00:17:08.890
in lines.

00:17:08.890 --> 00:17:11.619
And the lines are separated
from each other by some kind

00:17:11.619 --> 00:17:16.329
of a distance, here
represented by a capital D.

00:17:16.329 --> 00:17:20.440
And the reason that you
see the far-field pattern,

00:17:20.440 --> 00:17:22.329
we call that the far-field
pattern as opposed

00:17:22.329 --> 00:17:23.440
to the near-field pattern.

00:17:23.440 --> 00:17:30.601
If I were to do this
and put it very close,

00:17:30.601 --> 00:17:32.350
then I would think
about the pattern being

00:17:32.350 --> 00:17:36.830
the near-field pattern if
I get close compared to D.

00:17:36.830 --> 00:17:40.940
So if the slits are D apart,
the near-field is D close,

00:17:40.940 --> 00:17:44.920
and the far field is when
I'm far away compared to D.

00:17:44.920 --> 00:17:47.450
So if I'm far away
compared to D,

00:17:47.450 --> 00:17:52.050
then you can imagine that the
light is coming in this way,

00:17:52.050 --> 00:17:55.680
and each one of these
generates scatter.

00:17:55.680 --> 00:17:58.230
So there is a spherical
wave coming way out

00:17:58.230 --> 00:18:00.207
from each of these.

00:18:00.207 --> 00:18:01.290
That's Huygens' principle.

00:18:01.290 --> 00:18:03.300
Right

00:18:03.300 --> 00:18:06.870
So the idea then is that
there are contributions

00:18:06.870 --> 00:18:08.430
from each one of
these scatterers

00:18:08.430 --> 00:18:10.620
out here in the far field.

00:18:10.620 --> 00:18:12.450
Each point in the
far field picks up

00:18:12.450 --> 00:18:16.340
a little bit of light from
each of the scatterers,

00:18:16.340 --> 00:18:20.070
but they're in different
phase relationships.

00:18:20.070 --> 00:18:26.430
They were in phase when the
coherent light struck these.

00:18:26.430 --> 00:18:30.230
But now if I were to
think about a point here,

00:18:30.230 --> 00:18:34.505
the phase that you get is
different from the point here.

00:18:34.505 --> 00:18:41.150
So here the phase from two
points would be about the same.

00:18:41.150 --> 00:18:46.220
Here they would be different
because the distance traveled

00:18:46.220 --> 00:18:49.220
from this scatterer
is that much longer.

00:18:53.020 --> 00:18:57.280
So if I look at a
particular angle,

00:18:57.280 --> 00:19:02.560
then each of these scatterers is
a different optical path length

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:06.290
from the source.

00:19:06.290 --> 00:19:14.020
That means that if I arrange the
angle so that this is lambda,

00:19:14.020 --> 00:19:16.480
the light that
scatters off of here

00:19:16.480 --> 00:19:18.610
will constructively
interfere with the light that

00:19:18.610 --> 00:19:22.540
scatters off of here and here.

00:19:22.540 --> 00:19:25.080
Everybody see that?

00:19:25.080 --> 00:19:29.130
So that means that there's a
funny angle, the sign of which

00:19:29.130 --> 00:19:32.090
is lambda over D in which you
get constructive interference,

00:19:32.090 --> 00:19:34.800
and that's what's going on
with the diffraction grating.

00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:40.640
And you can see that.

00:19:40.640 --> 00:19:43.380
There are several illustrations
of that all over the place.

00:19:43.380 --> 00:19:45.930
Here I have a CD and a DVD.

00:19:45.930 --> 00:19:48.300
Which one is which?

00:19:48.300 --> 00:19:51.380
I'm showing you the
backside of a CD and a DVD.

00:19:51.380 --> 00:19:52.890
AUDIENCE: DVD is
in the left side.

00:19:52.890 --> 00:19:54.536
DENNIS FREEMAN:
DVDs is this one.

00:19:54.536 --> 00:19:55.410
How do you know that?

00:19:55.410 --> 00:19:56.710
AUDIENCE: Because it looks blue.

00:19:56.710 --> 00:19:58.293
DENNIS FREEMAN:
Because it looks blue.

00:19:58.293 --> 00:19:59.700
Why does it look blue?

00:19:59.700 --> 00:20:00.740
Not a clue.

00:20:00.740 --> 00:20:03.752
It's just they always do.

00:20:03.752 --> 00:20:05.150
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:05.150 --> 00:20:07.050
DENNIS FREEMAN: Smaller.

00:20:07.050 --> 00:20:11.340
So somehow this one reflects
better, the bluer lights,

00:20:11.340 --> 00:20:13.140
so you see more of
that, and this one

00:20:13.140 --> 00:20:16.790
reflects better longer lights.

00:20:16.790 --> 00:20:19.090
This one has got a
greenish twinge maybe.

00:20:22.660 --> 00:20:24.130
Kind of like all colors.

00:20:24.130 --> 00:20:26.110
I like to call it green.

00:20:26.110 --> 00:20:29.390
Maybe it's because
I know the answer.

00:20:29.390 --> 00:20:32.500
So if I take these guys, I can
get the same sort of thing,

00:20:32.500 --> 00:20:35.110
so I'll take the CD first.

00:20:35.110 --> 00:20:37.629
Now, of course, this
has a coding on it,

00:20:37.629 --> 00:20:39.670
so if I try to shine a
laser straight through it,

00:20:39.670 --> 00:20:41.950
not much will happen.

00:20:41.950 --> 00:20:46.180
I don't really want
to blind somebody.

00:20:46.180 --> 00:20:47.680
So I'm going to
take this and I'm

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:50.050
going to attempt to hit this
while watching back here,

00:20:50.050 --> 00:20:52.330
which for somebody my age
it's pretty hard to do.

00:20:52.330 --> 00:20:55.720
But the idea is going to be
that instead of using this

00:20:55.720 --> 00:20:58.690
as a transmission grating, I'm
going to use it as a reflection

00:20:58.690 --> 00:20:59.810
grating.

00:20:59.810 --> 00:21:00.925
So if I do this--

00:21:05.200 --> 00:21:06.880
so that's kind of cute.

00:21:06.880 --> 00:21:11.680
So my laser is green.

00:21:11.680 --> 00:21:13.795
What's lambda?

00:21:13.795 --> 00:21:14.785
AUDIENCE: 530.

00:21:14.785 --> 00:21:16.030
DENNIS FREEMAN: 530.

00:21:16.030 --> 00:21:16.930
So let's round off.

00:21:16.930 --> 00:21:17.941
Let's say 500.

00:21:17.941 --> 00:21:18.440
Yes.

00:21:21.310 --> 00:21:25.900
So I've got a green
laser, and what

00:21:25.900 --> 00:21:29.954
will happen if I move
the laser back and forth?

00:21:29.954 --> 00:21:31.120
How will the pattern change?

00:21:35.072 --> 00:21:37.050
It won't change.

00:21:37.050 --> 00:21:41.960
So if I do this, which I can't
do while I'm watching it,

00:21:41.960 --> 00:21:43.730
no change.

00:21:43.730 --> 00:21:45.669
What will happen if I
move this way this way?

00:21:50.122 --> 00:21:51.455
Well, the angle is what matters.

00:21:54.230 --> 00:21:58.760
So as I move it farther away,
the pattern gets bigger.

00:21:58.760 --> 00:22:08.720
So if I do this, if I were at
all coordinated, which I'm not,

00:22:08.720 --> 00:22:10.190
I'm trusting that
it's doing what

00:22:10.190 --> 00:22:14.150
I'm telling it to because I
can't look at the same time.

00:22:14.150 --> 00:22:21.110
So let me put this at a
precise 1 meter away, 3 feet.

00:22:21.110 --> 00:22:24.560
And let me shine this
in here, and let me

00:22:24.560 --> 00:22:26.690
do a very precise measurement.

00:22:26.690 --> 00:22:30.255
And those are now one-foot
apart by my precise measurement

00:22:30.255 --> 00:22:30.755
skills.

00:22:34.570 --> 00:22:39.420
So what I'd like you to do
is figure out the pitch.

00:22:39.420 --> 00:22:43.860
The information on a CD
is written will spirally.

00:22:43.860 --> 00:22:47.700
That's the reason there
is an apparent color.

00:22:47.700 --> 00:22:50.220
I just measured the pitch.

00:22:50.220 --> 00:22:52.290
How far apart are the tracks?

00:22:52.290 --> 00:22:54.780
So take the data.

00:22:54.780 --> 00:22:57.330
So if I'm three feet
away from the screen,

00:22:57.330 --> 00:22:59.100
the dots are
separated by one foot

00:22:59.100 --> 00:23:02.640
and figure out how closely
spaced the tracks are on a CD.

00:24:25.045 --> 00:24:25.920
So what's the answer?

00:24:25.920 --> 00:24:27.560
1, 2, 3, 4.

00:24:27.560 --> 00:24:28.310
None of the above.

00:24:34.580 --> 00:24:41.210
A very small number of
votes, but about 90% correct.

00:24:41.210 --> 00:24:41.900
So what do I do?

00:24:41.900 --> 00:24:42.858
How do I figure it out?

00:24:50.100 --> 00:24:50.600
Yeah.

00:24:50.600 --> 00:24:54.830
So we just made a
big deal out of how

00:24:54.830 --> 00:24:59.270
the distance, which
was D sine theta

00:24:59.270 --> 00:25:02.281
had to be an integer
multiple of lambda.

00:25:02.281 --> 00:25:04.280
So all we need to do is
think through some trig.

00:25:14.080 --> 00:25:15.520
So if I think about
the dots being

00:25:15.520 --> 00:25:18.320
a foot apart when I'm three feet
away, then the tangent is 1/3.

00:25:21.528 --> 00:25:26.749
So the small angle
approximation is about 1/3,

00:25:26.749 --> 00:25:27.790
so the sine is about 1/3.

00:25:31.450 --> 00:25:37.960
So lambda is about 500
nanometers divided by 1/3.

00:25:37.960 --> 00:25:41.410
And if I carry that out a little
more precisely, I get 1,613,

00:25:41.410 --> 00:25:43.900
and the manufacturer's
specification for CDs

00:25:43.900 --> 00:25:46.670
is 1,600 nanometers.

00:25:46.670 --> 00:25:51.070
So it's 1.6 micrometers.

00:25:51.070 --> 00:25:51.729
Yeah.

00:25:51.729 --> 00:25:55.082
AUDIENCE: [? What ?] is the
precision on [INAUDIBLE]??

00:25:55.082 --> 00:25:58.670
DENNIS FREEMAN: Oh,
they're pretty good.

00:25:58.670 --> 00:26:01.410
In fact, we'll talk about
this a little later.

00:26:01.410 --> 00:26:03.690
They do this by an
embossing process.

00:26:03.690 --> 00:26:09.450
So you make a master
out of aluminum,

00:26:09.450 --> 00:26:11.090
and then you stamp it.

00:26:11.090 --> 00:26:14.370
And the stamping is
actually very good.

00:26:14.370 --> 00:26:16.680
So probably the biggest
manufacturing problem

00:26:16.680 --> 00:26:18.090
is the thermals.

00:26:18.090 --> 00:26:24.360
So you stamp it in heated
polystyrene, so there's

00:26:24.360 --> 00:26:27.314
a little bit of a coefficient
of shrinkage as it cools,

00:26:27.314 --> 00:26:28.230
but it's not very big.

00:26:28.230 --> 00:26:30.300
It's fractions of a percent.

00:26:33.330 --> 00:26:38.140
So what will happen then
if I switch to the DVD,

00:26:38.140 --> 00:26:41.330
how many tracks are on a DVD?

00:26:41.330 --> 00:26:43.540
So we can do the same
kind of an experiment.

00:26:43.540 --> 00:26:48.174
Now if I try to do
the DVD, in order

00:26:48.174 --> 00:26:50.590
to get them to be a foot apart,
I have to get much closer.

00:26:53.674 --> 00:26:56.340
So now to get D space at about a
foot, I have to be about a foot

00:26:56.340 --> 00:26:57.420
away.

00:26:57.420 --> 00:27:03.140
So what's the spacing on
the DVD, smaller or bigger?

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:09.760
So it's smaller because
the angle got bigger.

00:27:09.760 --> 00:27:13.510
So it's the same sort of deal.

00:27:13.510 --> 00:27:20.140
If you think about the one foot,
so you get one-foot spacing

00:27:20.140 --> 00:27:20.995
with about one foot.

00:27:23.820 --> 00:27:25.830
So then the tangent is about 1.

00:27:25.830 --> 00:27:29.910
It's not quite a
small angle anymore.

00:27:29.910 --> 00:27:35.980
So theta is 0.78.

00:27:35.980 --> 00:27:41.410
And so the experimental value
comes out about 704 nanometers,

00:27:41.410 --> 00:27:46.730
so it's about a factor of 2.

00:27:46.730 --> 00:27:48.710
Smaller.

00:27:48.710 --> 00:27:50.540
So we got about
700 nano, so it's

00:27:50.540 --> 00:27:53.837
a fraction of a micron,
rather than 1.6 microns,

00:27:53.837 --> 00:27:55.670
and that's why they
look a little different.

00:27:55.670 --> 00:27:59.930
So we get about a factor of 2
in terms of information density

00:27:59.930 --> 00:28:01.941
in terms of track count.

00:28:01.941 --> 00:28:04.190
Of course, the information
is also stored more closely

00:28:04.190 --> 00:28:06.660
within a track as well.

00:28:06.660 --> 00:28:08.680
So instead of being about
a factor of 2 better,

00:28:08.680 --> 00:28:12.020
it's maybe a factor of 4
better because the track

00:28:12.020 --> 00:28:13.290
is based about a factor of 2.

00:28:17.260 --> 00:28:18.850
You can do more
interesting things.

00:28:18.850 --> 00:28:20.474
That's kind of the
most degenerate case

00:28:20.474 --> 00:28:26.800
because that's one D.
So here is a fancier

00:28:26.800 --> 00:28:30.970
grating from my lab, which has
the property that if I shine

00:28:30.970 --> 00:28:37.070
the light through
