AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:46.175 --> 00:31:48.470
DENNIS FREEMAN: Take the
Fourier transform, of course.

00:31:52.870 --> 00:31:53.451
So the idea.

00:31:53.451 --> 00:31:55.700
So what would happen if the
target is more complicated

00:31:55.700 --> 00:31:58.460
than a grating, the
way to think about this

00:31:58.460 --> 00:32:01.760
is the think about just like
in the case of the grating,

00:32:01.760 --> 00:32:07.130
if you collect the light
that hits the far field,

00:32:07.130 --> 00:32:10.050
the far field bit has a
point in the far field,

00:32:10.050 --> 00:32:14.780
came from all over the target
just like in the grating.

00:32:14.780 --> 00:32:18.230
In the grating, the
point in the far field

00:32:18.230 --> 00:32:20.300
came from every one
of the lines and there

00:32:20.300 --> 00:32:22.605
was a simple relationship
among the phases that

00:32:22.605 --> 00:32:24.230
came from each of
the lines, and that's

00:32:24.230 --> 00:32:27.410
what gave rise to the
pattern in the far field.

00:32:27.410 --> 00:32:29.280
Well, the same thing
is always true.

00:32:29.280 --> 00:32:33.780
All the points in the image
in the far field came from--

00:32:33.780 --> 00:32:37.580
each point, had contributions
from every point in the target.

00:32:40.270 --> 00:32:44.030
And if you think about
points in the target,

00:32:44.030 --> 00:32:46.240
now I'm going to think
about just one point

00:32:46.240 --> 00:32:48.880
so this is the target space.

00:32:48.880 --> 00:32:52.870
Way out there is the far field.

00:32:52.870 --> 00:32:56.560
So in the target space,
there's an x-coordinate,

00:32:56.560 --> 00:32:59.770
there's a y-coordinate,
there's a z-coordinate.

00:32:59.770 --> 00:33:03.130
Let me just worry
about x for the moment.

00:33:03.130 --> 00:33:08.440
This point that is x
displaced in this direction

00:33:08.440 --> 00:33:13.090
contributes a different
phase to the far field

00:33:13.090 --> 00:33:14.980
than a point that's at 0.

00:33:14.980 --> 00:33:18.420
Because the point is at x,
you get a different phase.

00:33:18.420 --> 00:33:21.610
And that phase relationship
depends, not just

00:33:21.610 --> 00:33:25.600
on x, but also on the angle.

00:33:25.600 --> 00:33:29.290
And this is the relationship,
the phase generated

00:33:29.290 --> 00:33:31.840
by a scatterer at the point, x.

00:33:34.370 --> 00:33:36.470
Just like the
one-dimensional grating,

00:33:36.470 --> 00:33:39.560
if you take x and
multiply by the sine,

00:33:39.560 --> 00:33:43.460
that tells you the
delay in meters,

00:33:43.460 --> 00:33:45.710
but then you can convert
that into radians

00:33:45.710 --> 00:33:51.630
by dividing by the wavelength
and multiplying by 2 pi.

00:33:51.630 --> 00:33:57.020
So the phase that is
generated by scattering

00:33:57.020 --> 00:34:00.170
from this point
displaced a distance, x,

00:34:00.170 --> 00:34:04.264
when measured in angle,
theta, in the far field,

00:34:04.264 --> 00:34:04.930
looks like that.

00:34:07.790 --> 00:34:11.179
That's supposed to be just
a simple reiteration of what

00:34:11.179 --> 00:34:13.420
we just did.

00:34:13.420 --> 00:34:17.050
Now the tricky part is
that all of the light that

00:34:17.050 --> 00:34:20.409
hits a particular
point in the far field,

00:34:20.409 --> 00:34:24.010
a point in the far field
is characterized as theta.

00:34:24.010 --> 00:34:26.320
Where is my laser pointer?

00:34:26.320 --> 00:34:28.810
So if you go to the
far field at a place,

00:34:28.810 --> 00:34:34.620
theta, the total amount of light
that hits the point, theta,

00:34:34.620 --> 00:34:39.150
is the sum, the integral, of
all the different scatterers.

00:34:39.150 --> 00:34:41.159
So f is x represents
how much light gets

00:34:41.159 --> 00:34:43.859
scattered as a function of x.

00:34:43.859 --> 00:34:46.900
x is the target.

00:34:46.900 --> 00:34:50.040
So this is integrating
over how much

00:34:50.040 --> 00:34:53.850
light gets scattered at each
x, and at a particular x,

00:34:53.850 --> 00:34:55.179
you get this phase delay.

00:34:57.680 --> 00:35:01.650
So there's a coherent sum then.

00:35:01.650 --> 00:35:04.030
So you add up all of
these complex numbers

00:35:04.030 --> 00:35:06.870
by the integral.

00:35:06.870 --> 00:35:10.660
Now imagine that the sine
of theta is about theta.

00:35:10.660 --> 00:35:13.730
That was true all of the
examples I've done so far.

00:35:13.730 --> 00:35:17.780
So here I'm what, 15 feet
away, and it's a foot,

00:35:17.780 --> 00:35:21.250
so that's small
angle approximation.

00:35:21.250 --> 00:35:25.800
So now let's replace
sine of theta with theta,

00:35:25.800 --> 00:35:29.190
and let's think about this
number, 2 pi theta over lambda.

00:35:29.190 --> 00:35:32.730
That's just frequency omega.

00:35:32.730 --> 00:35:34.920
So I'm thinking about
now the far field,

00:35:34.920 --> 00:35:38.560
which we had previously
called dependent on theta.

00:35:38.560 --> 00:35:41.890
Theta is just omega.

00:35:41.890 --> 00:35:45.520
So I've got a relationship now
between how much scattering

00:35:45.520 --> 00:35:51.430
happens at each x in the target
and what does the picture

00:35:51.430 --> 00:35:53.650
look like in the far field.

00:35:53.650 --> 00:35:56.970
And that's a Fourier transform.

00:35:56.970 --> 00:35:59.360
So there is an exact Fourier
transform relationship.

00:35:59.360 --> 00:36:03.080
Well, exact is a little
bit of an approximation

00:36:03.080 --> 00:36:05.270
because I'm using a small
angle approximation.

00:36:05.270 --> 00:36:07.380
I'm ignoring a few things.

00:36:07.380 --> 00:36:10.250
Not only am I making a
small angle approximation,

00:36:10.250 --> 00:36:12.380
but I'm assuming that if
the light goes straight

00:36:12.380 --> 00:36:15.950
and if the light goes up, they
have the same intensity when

00:36:15.950 --> 00:36:17.780
they hit the board.

00:36:17.780 --> 00:36:18.770
That's not quite true.

00:36:18.770 --> 00:36:21.950
That's with Fraunhofer
approximation blah, blah, blah.

00:36:21.950 --> 00:36:23.840
Fancy names for a bunch
of approximations.

00:36:23.840 --> 00:36:27.170
The point is that if you make
reasonable approximations,

00:36:27.170 --> 00:36:29.150
you get a Fourier
transform relationship

00:36:29.150 --> 00:36:33.320
between the scattering in the
target and far field image.

00:36:40.110 --> 00:36:42.600
So now we have a
very convenient way

00:36:42.600 --> 00:36:46.380
of thinking about what
happened whenever I shot

00:36:46.380 --> 00:36:49.050
my laser through this thing.

00:36:49.050 --> 00:36:54.390
I get a bunch of spots in
the far field because--

00:36:59.380 --> 00:37:01.210
everybody shout.

00:37:01.210 --> 00:37:02.000
This is the aha.

00:37:05.460 --> 00:37:11.610
So we've got an impulse train
in the Fourier transform, which

00:37:11.610 --> 00:37:17.670
means that the thing that was
down here was an impulse train.

00:37:17.670 --> 00:37:20.400
because we know that the Fourier
transform of an impulse train

00:37:20.400 --> 00:37:23.010
is an impulse train.

00:37:23.010 --> 00:37:26.620
So this is an impulse
train in space.

00:37:26.620 --> 00:37:29.920
The scatterers represent
an impulse train.

00:37:29.920 --> 00:37:32.810
So whenever I illuminate
it, I getting impulse train

00:37:32.810 --> 00:37:35.470
in the free transform
because the Fourier

00:37:35.470 --> 00:37:37.519
transfer on an impulse
train is an impulse train.

00:37:37.519 --> 00:37:38.560
Well, that's pretty cool.

00:37:42.790 --> 00:37:47.620
So you all know why an impulse
train is an impulse train.

00:37:47.620 --> 00:37:51.940
So this two dimensional grating
then, the interesting thing

00:37:51.940 --> 00:37:54.460
about that then
is that it must be

00:37:54.460 --> 00:38:02.470
the case that the Fourier
transform of a 2D impulse train

00:38:02.470 --> 00:38:04.390
is a 2D impulse train.

00:38:04.390 --> 00:38:07.450
So I want to think just
a minute about that.

00:38:07.450 --> 00:38:10.900
What will we mean by a
two-dimensional Fourier

00:38:10.900 --> 00:38:12.557
transform.

00:38:12.557 --> 00:38:14.140
So two-dimensional
Fourier transforms.

00:38:14.140 --> 00:38:20.440
I want x j omega 1, j omega 2.

00:38:20.440 --> 00:38:25.150
So it's a lot like
a 1D transform.

00:38:25.150 --> 00:38:29.410
I am going to think about having
x except now there's two time

00:38:29.410 --> 00:38:33.046
variables, time 1 and time 2.

00:38:33.046 --> 00:38:34.420
And I'm going to
have to have two

00:38:34.420 --> 00:38:36.730
of these funny
exponential things.

00:38:36.730 --> 00:38:38.500
So I'm going to have
e to the minus j

00:38:38.500 --> 00:38:49.980
omega 1 t1 plus
omega 2 t2 d t1 d t2.

00:38:49.980 --> 00:38:53.040
It's almost like a 1D transform
except I have two d's now.

00:38:56.700 --> 00:38:59.400
And the way to think
about that, probably

00:38:59.400 --> 00:39:00.780
shouldn't distract
you with this.

00:39:00.780 --> 00:39:01.696
That's the next slide.

00:39:06.550 --> 00:39:12.130
So the way to think about
this is this separates.

00:39:12.130 --> 00:39:16.750
e to the j sum is e to
the j1 plus e to the j2.

00:39:16.750 --> 00:39:24.550
So I can write this more simply
as x of t1, t2 e to the minus j

00:39:24.550 --> 00:39:28.960
omega 1 t1 d t1.

00:39:28.960 --> 00:39:34.080
So then I can integrate that,
e to the minus j omega d t2.

00:39:38.230 --> 00:39:41.940
This is the integral
over the t1 variable.

00:39:44.820 --> 00:39:47.930
So if I think about doing
the transform in steps,

00:39:47.930 --> 00:39:49.580
this is the integral
I might say--

00:39:49.580 --> 00:39:57.250
so let's say that I had
my original 2D thing

00:39:57.250 --> 00:39:59.090
was a square that I'd
like to characterize

00:39:59.090 --> 00:40:04.470
as a t1 dependence
and a t2 dependence.

00:40:04.470 --> 00:40:06.590
The way I think about
the 2D transform,

00:40:06.590 --> 00:40:14.170
this thing says, for each
t2, treat t2 as a constant,

00:40:14.170 --> 00:40:16.870
for each t2, that's
for each row.

00:40:16.870 --> 00:40:20.080
Treat t2 as a constant and
just take the Fourier transform

00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:23.470
of the t1 direction.

00:40:23.470 --> 00:40:32.190
So what I do is I take the
Fourier transform of this,

00:40:32.190 --> 00:40:35.460
and I put it here, but
when I've done that,

00:40:35.460 --> 00:40:39.810
I've changed the t1 axis
into an omega 1 axis

00:40:39.810 --> 00:40:42.210
because the result of
integrating over t1

00:40:42.210 --> 00:40:44.640
throws away the t1, but
I'm left with an omega 1.

00:40:47.940 --> 00:40:52.980
If I repeat that for
all the different lines,

00:40:52.980 --> 00:40:56.160
I didn't really change
this axis, which was t2,

00:40:56.160 --> 00:40:57.310
so it's still t2.

00:40:59.914 --> 00:41:01.330
All I've done now
is taken a bunch

00:41:01.330 --> 00:41:02.620
of integrals in the middle.

00:41:02.620 --> 00:41:06.670
Now, if I take the outer
integral, what I need to do

00:41:06.670 --> 00:41:09.340
is integrate over t2.

00:41:09.340 --> 00:41:19.481
So if I integrate over t2, now
I want to integrate this way.

00:41:19.481 --> 00:41:20.980
Now, I want to
integrate out the t2.

00:41:20.980 --> 00:41:23.930
The t2 goes away.

00:41:23.930 --> 00:41:26.290
So I take Fourier
transforms this way.

00:41:26.290 --> 00:41:29.530
For each column in
this space, I generate

00:41:29.530 --> 00:41:33.520
a new Fourier transform
over here, and I repeat.

00:41:33.520 --> 00:41:34.780
That doesn't change this one.

00:41:34.780 --> 00:41:36.640
This one is still omega 1.

00:41:36.640 --> 00:41:39.460
But then when I take the
transform this way, I had a t2.

00:41:39.460 --> 00:41:42.820
That turns it into an omega 2.

00:41:42.820 --> 00:41:48.580
So I started with t1-t2 space,
take all the transforms row

00:41:48.580 --> 00:41:53.440
wise, make a new array, take
all the transforms column wise,

00:41:53.440 --> 00:41:55.840
make a new array, and I end
up with omega 1, omega 2.

00:41:59.160 --> 00:42:10.360
So if I do that, what's the
two-dimensional transform?

00:42:10.360 --> 00:42:12.010
What if I started
with a vertical line?

00:42:14.920 --> 00:42:17.380
What if my spatial dependence
had a vertical line in it?

00:42:17.380 --> 00:42:19.960
What would be the
two-dimensional transform

00:42:19.960 --> 00:42:20.770
of a vertical line?

00:42:25.730 --> 00:42:31.730
Well, the rule says
transform all the rows.

00:42:31.730 --> 00:42:33.942
What's the transform?

00:42:33.942 --> 00:42:35.150
What do I call that function?

00:42:39.380 --> 00:42:40.161
Shout.

00:42:40.161 --> 00:42:40.660
I'm deaf.

00:42:40.660 --> 00:42:42.308
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:42.308 --> 00:42:45.890
DENNIS FREEMAN: So let's say
the line has a height of 1,

00:42:45.890 --> 00:42:49.610
and the background
has a height of 0.

00:42:49.610 --> 00:42:53.620
So as I read across here
it's, 0 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0.

00:42:53.620 --> 00:42:55.021
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:57.823 --> 00:43:00.390
DENNIS FREEMAN: Exponential.

00:43:00.390 --> 00:43:01.260
Impulse.

00:43:01.260 --> 00:43:03.450
Impulse in left.

00:43:03.450 --> 00:43:06.660
So when I take the
transform, I get 1.

00:43:06.660 --> 00:43:07.860
I get constant.

00:43:07.860 --> 00:43:13.920
So I get a constant over here,
and then I take this one.

00:43:13.920 --> 00:43:15.240
Same thing.

00:43:15.240 --> 00:43:17.250
Same constant, same
constant, same constant.

00:43:17.250 --> 00:43:19.990
I end up with a
constant over here.

00:43:19.990 --> 00:43:24.790
So this started out
being delta of t1.

00:43:24.790 --> 00:43:27.070
This is a constant everywhere.

00:43:27.070 --> 00:43:34.550
So now if I take the
column-wise transforms,

00:43:34.550 --> 00:43:36.474
what's the transform
of a constant?

00:43:40.694 --> 00:43:41.360
It's an impulse.

00:43:41.360 --> 00:43:42.526
Where should the impulse be?

00:43:44.860 --> 00:43:46.670
0.

00:43:46.670 --> 00:43:52.790
So I end up when I do the
omega 2, the t2 transforms.

00:43:52.790 --> 00:43:54.890
I get a delta in omega 2.

00:43:54.890 --> 00:43:59.270
So I have omega 1 here,
and I have omega 2 here.

00:43:59.270 --> 00:44:04.320
So I end up with a delta
function like that.

00:44:04.320 --> 00:44:06.030
Then I do it again,
and I get one here.

00:44:06.030 --> 00:44:07.840
And then I do it again,
and I get one here.

00:44:07.840 --> 00:44:10.000
So I end up with a line.

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:13.070
So vertical line in t1-t2 space
turns into a horizontal line

00:44:13.070 --> 00:44:16.270
in omega 1-omega 2 space.

00:44:16.270 --> 00:44:17.470
Got it?

00:44:17.470 --> 00:44:20.110
It's all very simple.

00:44:20.110 --> 00:44:23.680
And if I do the same thing,
if I did a horizontal line,

00:44:23.680 --> 00:44:26.060
it will come out vertical.

00:44:26.060 --> 00:44:28.530
And if I do a diagonal
line, it will rotate 90.

00:44:31.590 --> 00:44:33.240
Very cute.

00:44:33.240 --> 00:44:34.710
Y'all got it?

00:44:34.710 --> 00:44:39.660
So the idea then is that there's
a very natural generalization

00:44:39.660 --> 00:44:42.390
from a 1D transform
to a 2D transform,

00:44:42.390 --> 00:44:46.180
and that's kind of fun, but
it's also kind of important.

00:44:46.180 --> 00:44:47.820
So now for the important part.

00:44:47.820 --> 00:44:57.570
So this is a picture, a
diffraction photomicrograph

00:44:57.570 --> 00:45:02.880
done by Rosalind Franklin
back about 50 years ago.

00:45:02.880 --> 00:45:04.192
She had taken DNA.

00:45:04.192 --> 00:45:04.900
I can't remember.

00:45:04.900 --> 00:45:07.410
I think it was from Drosophila,
but I don't really remember.

00:45:07.410 --> 00:45:09.660
She had purified DNA.

00:45:09.660 --> 00:45:14.700
And at that time, lasers
were not this size.

00:45:14.700 --> 00:45:15.900
Actually, she used x-rays.

00:45:15.900 --> 00:45:18.170
She used a source of
coherent light from an x-ray,

00:45:18.170 --> 00:45:22.140
so it's not even a
laser, it was x-rays.

00:45:22.140 --> 00:45:27.960
She fired coherent
x-rays at DNA--

00:45:27.960 --> 00:45:30.990
so she had just a
big glob of DNA--

00:45:30.990 --> 00:45:34.330
and took this picture.

00:45:34.330 --> 00:45:37.870
And it was pretty
and pretty confusing.

00:45:37.870 --> 00:45:40.270
By the way, just so you
know, this is an artifact.

00:45:40.270 --> 00:45:45.100
This is a hole in the
photographic film.

00:45:45.100 --> 00:45:49.660
So the idea was coherent source
of x-rays, sample of DNA,

00:45:49.660 --> 00:45:51.720
into a photographic emotion.

00:45:51.720 --> 00:45:53.334
Develop it, you get this.

00:45:53.334 --> 00:45:55.750
So it's very similar to the
diffraction grating experiment

00:45:55.750 --> 00:45:59.050
that I did except that the
target was not a diffraction

00:45:59.050 --> 00:46:04.030
grating, it was not a CD,
it was not a DVD, it was DNA

00:46:04.030 --> 00:46:06.220
That cute thing
is that she showed

00:46:06.220 --> 00:46:09.460
this to Watson and
Crick, who were

00:46:09.460 --> 00:46:13.150
geniuses at so many
different levels it's absurd,

00:46:13.150 --> 00:46:17.440
and especially Watson knew
all about Fourier transforms.

00:46:17.440 --> 00:46:19.600
And so he saw that
and immediately

00:46:19.600 --> 00:46:22.240
was able to interpret
it as telling him

00:46:22.240 --> 00:46:24.950
something about the
three-dimensional structure

00:46:24.950 --> 00:46:26.920
of DNA.

00:46:26.920 --> 00:46:32.200
In particular, if you think
about our modern view of DNA,

00:46:32.200 --> 00:46:34.540
you can make an association
between the structure

00:46:34.540 --> 00:46:39.150
of the DNA and this picture.

00:46:39.150 --> 00:46:41.950
So there's a
high-frequency band.

00:46:41.950 --> 00:46:44.710
So if you imagine that
what you're seeing

00:46:44.710 --> 00:46:49.390
is three bright points
from a diffraction pattern

00:46:49.390 --> 00:46:52.660
like I showed
previously, this and this

00:46:52.660 --> 00:46:54.880
represents a high frequency.

00:46:54.880 --> 00:46:57.100
This represents DC.

00:46:57.100 --> 00:47:00.010
So the distance between
DC and the high frequency

00:47:00.010 --> 00:47:03.970
is telling you something
about the inverse distance

00:47:03.970 --> 00:47:06.710
between base pairs.

00:47:06.710 --> 00:47:16.530
The highest frequency
in the x-ray picture

00:47:16.530 --> 00:47:18.740
is inversely related to the
distance between the base

00:47:18.740 --> 00:47:20.960
pairs.

00:47:20.960 --> 00:47:26.675
The fact that there is these
closer-spaced frequencies,

00:47:26.675 --> 00:47:28.670
those are actually
lower frequencies

00:47:28.670 --> 00:47:31.160
because they're closer to 0--

00:47:31.160 --> 00:47:34.550
we're in the far field, so
we're in the frequency domain.

00:47:34.550 --> 00:47:37.550
Big frequency, small frequency.

00:47:37.550 --> 00:47:41.450
The fact that we're seeing these
smaller frequency things here

00:47:41.450 --> 00:47:45.000
and there are periodic, that
means there some structure

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:50.610
at bigger spacing, which
Watson and Crick interpreted

00:47:50.610 --> 00:47:55.450
as the pitch of
the double helix.

00:47:55.450 --> 00:47:58.220
So the helix is twisting.

00:47:58.220 --> 00:48:00.230
This is the modern
picture, and it

00:48:00.230 --> 00:48:03.770
fits very nicely
with the picture

00:48:03.770 --> 00:48:09.140
that Rosalind Franklin made.

00:48:09.140 --> 00:48:15.700
And the angles, the fact
that there is an axis here,

00:48:15.700 --> 00:48:17.450
the reason for going
through all this junk

00:48:17.450 --> 00:48:19.130
was to motivate the
idea that there's

00:48:19.130 --> 00:48:22.870
an angle transformation in a
two-dimensional transform too.

00:48:22.870 --> 00:48:28.040
In fact, angles in space
get rotated 90 degrees

00:48:28.040 --> 00:48:30.780
when they're in frequency.

00:48:30.780 --> 00:48:33.740
So the angle between
these solid lines

00:48:33.740 --> 00:48:35.630
tells you something
about the angle

00:48:35.630 --> 00:48:39.750
that the helix makes as
it's wrapping around.

00:48:39.750 --> 00:48:44.150
So you can easily make 003
model of this experiment,

00:48:44.150 --> 00:48:45.560
and that's what this is.

00:48:45.560 --> 00:48:49.400
Here all I've taken
is a trivial model.

00:48:49.400 --> 00:48:53.990
I just made a wire
frame that had

00:48:53.990 --> 00:48:59.540
base pairs arranged as
a rotating spiral, just

00:48:59.540 --> 00:49:02.130
like a spiral staircase.

00:49:02.130 --> 00:49:04.380
Then that was a
three-dimensional picture.

00:49:04.380 --> 00:49:08.180
Then I just flattened
it, and then I

00:49:08.180 --> 00:49:11.180
took the two-dimensional
Fourier transform and got that.

00:49:14.810 --> 00:49:15.670
Got it?

00:49:15.670 --> 00:49:20.010
So the idea was I made a trivial
model for what DNA should look

00:49:20.010 --> 00:49:22.110
like according to a
modern conception,

00:49:22.110 --> 00:49:23.910
took the two-dimensional
Fourier transform,

00:49:23.910 --> 00:49:26.190
and what you can see there
is all of the features

00:49:26.190 --> 00:49:30.750
that you see in Rosalind
Franklin's picture.

00:49:30.750 --> 00:49:35.250
You can see the big band that
corresponds to the base pairs,

00:49:35.250 --> 00:49:38.100
you can see the smaller bands
that correspond to the twist,

00:49:38.100 --> 00:49:39.990
and you can see the
angle that corresponds

00:49:39.990 --> 00:49:42.780
to the angle of
the double helix.

00:49:42.780 --> 00:49:45.030
So the point then
is just that there's

00:49:45.030 --> 00:49:47.040
a lot of physical phenomenon.

00:49:47.040 --> 00:49:48.690
Besides the signal
processing things

00:49:48.690 --> 00:49:50.370
which we're very interested
in, there's actually

00:49:50.370 --> 00:49:51.745
a lot of physical
phenomenon that

00:49:51.745 --> 00:49:55.082
also have intrinsic meaning
within a Fourier domain,

00:49:55.082 --> 00:49:57.040
and optics is a very
important example of that.

00:50:00.180 --> 00:50:00.840
See you later.

00:50:00.840 --> 00:50:02.720
Have a good day.

